{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17586761","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17586761"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T08:38:55+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T08:38:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15098"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15098","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15098"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0,0.18,0.71,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7786"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66617"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7786","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7786"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15098"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52070"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4934"},{"type":"tags","id":"4945"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5326"},{"type":"tags","id":"5402"},{"type":"tags","id":"8131"},{"type":"tags","id":"10773"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18998"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19002"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22219"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66617","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66617"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EWhen taking a history from a patient with a suspected carcinoma of the prostate, it is important to seek information that might indicate a risk factor.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA medical student is researching risk factors for prostate cancer.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is correct?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["African ancestry doubles the risk compared to European ancestry","Asian ancestry carries the highest risk of all ethnic groups","Family history only matters if diagnosed before age 40 years","Having two first-degree relatives with prostate cancer increases risk by tenfold","Lynch syndrome significantly increases the risk"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EProstate cancer risk varies significantly by ancestry. \u003Cstrong\u003EAfrican ancestry\u003C/strong\u003E is associated with approximately double the risk of prostate cancer compared to European ancestry, and also tends to present at an earlier age with more aggressive disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe risk associated with having \u003Cstrong\u003Etwo first-degree relatives\u003C/strong\u003E with prostate cancer increases risk by about 5-fold, not tenfold. \u003Cstrong\u003ELynch syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is not significantly associated with prostate cancer risk, though BRCA1 and BRCA2 mutations do increase risk. \u003Cstrong\u003EFamily history\u003C/strong\u003E of prostate cancer increases risk regardless of age at diagnosis, though earlier age of diagnosis may indicate higher genetic risk. \u003Cstrong\u003EAsian ancestry\u003C/strong\u003E is actually associated with lower risk of prostate cancer compared to European and African ancestry.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["African ancestry is associated with higher prostate cancer risk compared to European ancestry","Family history of prostate cancer increases risk, particularly with multiple first-degree relatives","BRCA1/2 mutations, but not Lynch syndrome, increase prostate cancer risk"],"references":["Down L, Barlow M, Bailey SER, Mounce LTA, Merriel SWD, Watson J, Martins T. Association between patient ethnicity and prostate cancer diagnosis following a prostate-specific antigen test: a cohort study of 730,000 men in primary care in the UK. BMC Med. 2024 Mar 1;22(1):82. doi: 10.1186/s12916-024-03283-5. PMID: 38424555; PMCID: PMC10905783.","Rebbeck TR. Prostate Cancer Disparities by Race and Ethnicity: From Nucleotide to Neighborhood. Cold Spring Harb Perspect Med. 2018 Sep 4;8(9):a030387. doi: 10.1101/cshperspect.a030387. PMID: 29229666; PMCID: PMC6120694.","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science","Koeppen, B. M., \u0026 Stanton, B. A. (2018). Renal Physiology E-Book: Renal Physiology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52070"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15098"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52070","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52070"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-01T16:11:11+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-01T16:12:04+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7786"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66617"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"descript